013/**
014 * A palette of predefined colors as packed HSLuv floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with, plus a way to describe
015 * colors by combinations and adjustments. The description code is probably what you would use this class for; it
016 * revolves around {@link #parseDescription(String)}, which takes a color description String and returns a packed float
017 * color. The color descriptions look like "darker rich mint yellow", where the order of the words doesn't matter. They
018 * can optionally include lightness changes (light/dark), and saturation changes (rich/dull), and must include one or
019 * more color names that will be mixed together (repeats are allowed to use a color more heavily). The changes can be
020 * suffixed with "er", "est", or "most", such as "duller", "lightest", or "richmost", to progressively increase their
021 * effect on lightness or saturation.
022 * <br>
023 * The rest of this is about the same as in {@code Palette}.
024 * <br>
025 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code CACTUS}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
026 * {@code NAMED.get("cactus", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatArray called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
027 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
028 * will not occur in a valid HSLuv color. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
029 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
030 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
031 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
032 * <br>
033 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/13/2020.
034 */
035public class SimplePalette {
036    /**
037     * You can look up colors by name here; the names are lower-case, and the colors are packed floats in HSLuv format.
038     */
039    public static final ObjectFloatMap<String> NAMED = new ObjectFloatMap<String>(50);
040    /**
041     * Stores alternative names for colors in {@link #NAMED}, like "grey" as an alias for {@link #GRAY} or "gold" as an
042     * alias for {@link #SAFFRON}. Currently, the list of aliases is as follows:
043     * <ul>
044     * <li>"grey" maps to {@link #GRAY},</li>
045     * <li>"gold" maps to {@link #SAFFRON},</li>
046     * <li>"puce" maps to {@link #MAUVE},</li>
047     * <li>"sand" maps to {@link #TAN},</li>
048     * <li>"skin" maps to {@link #PEACH},</li>
049     * <li>"coral" maps to {@link #SALMON},</li>
050     * <li>"azure" maps to {@link #SKY}, and</li>
051     * <li>"ocean" maps to {@link #TEAL}, and</li>
052     * <li>"sapphire" maps to {@link #COBALT}.</li>
053     * </ul>
054     * Note that these aliases are not duplicated in {@link #NAMES}, {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE}, or
055     * {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS}; they are primarily there so blind attempts to name a color might still work.
056     */
057    public static final ObjectFloatMap<String> ALIASES = new ObjectFloatMap<String>(20);
058    /**

677     * All names for colors in this palette, sorted by lightness from black to white. You can fetch the
678     * corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
679     */
680    public static final Array<String> NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS = new Array<>(NAMES);
681    static {
682        NAMES_BY_HUE.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
683            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
684                final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT), c2 = NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT);
685                final float s1 = ColorTools.channelS(c1), s2 = ColorTools.channelS(c2);
686                if(alphaInt(c1) < 128) return -10000;
687                else if(alphaInt(c2) < 128) return 10000;
688                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 > 0.05f)
689                    return -1000;
690                else if(s1 > 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
691                    return 1000;
692                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
693                    return (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.channelL(c1) - ColorTools.channelL(c2));
694                else
695                    return 2 * (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.channelH(c1) - ColorTools.channelH(c2))
696                            + (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.channelL(c1) - ColorTools.channelL(c2));
697            }
698        });
699        for(String name : NAMES_BY_HUE) {
700            COLORS_BY_HUE.add(NAMED.get(name, TRANSPARENT));
701        }
702        NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
703            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
704                return Float.compare(channelL(NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT)), channelL(NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT)));
705            }
706        });

709    private static final FloatArray mixing = new FloatArray(4);
710
711    /**
712     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed float color.
713     * Color descriptions consist of one or more lower-case words, separated by non-alphabetical characters (typically
714     * spaces and/or hyphens). Any word that is the name of a color in this SimplePalette will be looked up in
715     * {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name words, the colors will be mixed using
716     * {@link ColorTools#mix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one color name word, then the corresponding color
717     * will be used. The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise,
718     * "rich" and "dull" change the saturation (the difference of the chromatic channels from grayscale). All of these
719     * adjectives can have "-er" or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically,
720     * the chars appended to an adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and
721     * "richcat" is the same as "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are
722     * appended to an adjective (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. If a color
723     * name or adjective is invalid, it is considered the same as adding the color {@link #TRANSPARENT}.
724     * <br>
725     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
726     * and "lightest richer apricot-olive".
727     * @param description a color description, as a lower-case String matching the above format
728     * @return a packed float color as described
729     */
730    public static float parseDescription(final String description) {
731        float lightness = 0f, saturation = 0f;
732        final String[] terms = description.split("[^a-zA-Z]+");
733        mixing.clear();
734        for(String term : terms) {
735            if (term == null || term.isEmpty()) continue;
736            final int len = term.length();
737            switch (term.charAt(0)) {
738                case 'l':
739                    if (len > 2 && term.charAt(2) == 'g') {
740                        switch (len) {
741                            case 9:
742                                lightness += 0.150f;
743                            case 8:
744                                lightness += 0.150f;
745                            case 7:
746                                lightness += 0.150f;
747                            case 5:
748                                lightness += 0.150f;
749                                continue;
750                        }
751                    }
752                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
753                    break;
754                case 'b':
755                    if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'g')) { // bright
756                        switch (len) {
757                            case 10:
758                                lightness += 0.150f;
759                                saturation += 0.200f;
760                            case 9:
761                                lightness += 0.150f;
762                                saturation += 0.200f;
763                            case 8:
764                                lightness += 0.150f;
765                                saturation += 0.200f;
766                            case 6:
767                                lightness += 0.150f;
768                                saturation += 0.200f;
769                                continue;
770                        }
771                    }
772                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
773                    break;
774                case 'p':
775                    if (len > 2 && (term.charAt(2) == 'l')) { // pale
776                        switch (len) {
777                            case 8: // palemost
778                            case 7: // palerer
779                                lightness += 0.150f;
780                                saturation -= 0.200f;
781                            case 6: // palest
782                                lightness += 0.150f;
783                                saturation -= 0.200f;
784                            case 5: // paler
785                                lightness += 0.150f;
786                                saturation -= 0.200f;
787                            case 4: // pale
788                                lightness += 0.150f;
789                                saturation -= 0.200f;
790                                continue;
791                        }
792                    }
793                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
794                    break;
795                case 'w':
796                    if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'k')) { // weak
797                        switch (len) {
798                            case 8:
799                                lightness -= 0.150f;
800                                saturation -= 0.200f;
801                            case 7:
802                                lightness -= 0.150f;
803                                saturation -= 0.200f;
804                            case 6:
805                                lightness -= 0.150f;
806                                saturation -= 0.200f;
807                            case 4:
808                                lightness -= 0.150f;
809                                saturation -= 0.200f;
810                                continue;
811                        }
812                    }
813                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
814                    break;
815                case 'r':
816                    if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'i')) { // rich
817                        switch (len) {
818                            case 8:
819                                saturation += 0.200f;
820                            case 7:
821                                saturation += 0.200f;
822                            case 6:
823                                saturation += 0.200f;
824                            case 4:
825                                saturation += 0.200f;
826                                continue;
827                        }
828                    }
829                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
830                    break;
831                case 'd':
832                    if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'a')) { // dark
833                        switch (len) {
834                            case 8:
835                                lightness -= 0.150f;
836                            case 7:
837                                lightness -= 0.150f;
838                            case 6:
839                                lightness -= 0.150f;
840                            case 4:
841                                lightness -= 0.150f;
842                                continue;
843                        }
844                    } else if (len > 1 && (term.charAt(1) == 'u')) { // dull
845                        switch (len) {
846                            case 8:
847                                saturation -= 0.200f;
848                            case 7:
849                                saturation -= 0.200f;
850                            case 6:
851                                saturation -= 0.200f;
852                            case 4:
853                                saturation -= 0.200f;
854                                continue;
855                        }
856                    } else if (len > 3 && (term.charAt(3) == 'p')) { // deep
857                        switch (len) {
858                            case 8:
859                                lightness -= 0.150f;
860                                saturation += 0.200f;
861                            case 7:
862                                lightness -= 0.150f;
863                                saturation += 0.200f;
864                            case 6:
865                                lightness -= 0.150f;
866                                saturation += 0.200f;
867                            case 4:
868                                lightness -= 0.150f;
869                                saturation += 0.200f;
870                                continue;
871                        }
872                    }
873                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
874                    break;
875                default:
876                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
877                    break;
878            }
879        }
880        float result = mix(mixing.items, 0, mixing.size);
881        if(result == 0f) return result;
882
883        if(lightness > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, lightness);
884        else if(lightness < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -lightness);
885
886        if(saturation > 0) result = (ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation));
887        else if(saturation < 0) result = (ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation));
888//        else result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(result);
889
890        return result;
891    }

947    /**
948     * Given a color as a packed HSLuv float, this finds the closest description it can to match the given color while
949     * using at most {@code mixCount} colors to mix in. You should only use small numbers for mixCount, like 1 to 3;
950     * this can take quite a while to run otherwise. This returns a String description that can be passed to
951     * {@link #parseDescription(String)}. It is likely that this will use very contrasting colors if mixCount is 2 or
952     * greater and the color to match is desaturated or brownish.
953     * @param hsluv a packed HSLuv float color to attempt to match
954     * @param mixCount how many color names this will use in the returned description
955     * @return a description that can be fed to {@link #parseDescription(String)} to get a similar color
956     */
957    public static String bestMatch(final float hsluv, int mixCount) {
958        mixCount = Math.max(1, mixCount);
959        float bestDistance = Float.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
960        final int paletteSize = namesByHue.size, colorTries = (int)Math.pow(paletteSize, mixCount), totalTries = colorTries * 81;
961        final float targetH = ColorTools.channelH(hsluv), targetS = ColorTools.channelS(hsluv), targetL = ColorTools.channelL(hsluv);
962        mixing.clear();
963        for (int i = 0; i < mixCount; i++) {
964            mixing.add(colorsByHue.get(0));
965        }
966        int bestCode = 0;
967        for (int c = 0; c < totalTries; c++) {
968            for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; i++, e *= paletteSize) {
969                mixing.set(i, colorsByHue.get((c / e) % paletteSize));
970            }
971            int idxL = ((c / colorTries) % 9 - 4), idxS = (c / (colorTries * 9) - 4);
972
973            float result = mix(mixing.items, 0, mixCount);
974            if(idxL > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, 0.15f * idxL);
975            else if(idxL < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -0.15f * idxL);
976
977            if(idxS > 0) result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(ColorTools.enrich(result, 0.2f * idxS));
978            else if(idxS < 0) result = ColorTools.dullen(result, -0.2f * idxS);
979
980            float dH = Math.abs(ColorTools.channelH(result) - targetH), dS = ColorTools.channelS(result) - targetS, dL = ColorTools.channelL(result) - targetL;
981            if(dH > 0.5f) dH = 1f - dH;
982            if(bestDistance > (bestDistance = Math.min(dH * dH + dS * dS + dL * dL, bestDistance)))
983                bestCode = c;
984        }
985
986        StringBuilder description = new StringBuilder(combinedAdjectives[(bestCode / colorTries)]);
987        for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; e *= paletteSize) {
988            description.append(namesByHue.get((bestCode / e) % paletteSize));
989            if(++i < mixCount)
990                description.append(' ');
991        }
992        return description.toString();
993    }

1007            final float f = ColorTools.fromColor(c);
1008            c.set(channelH(f), channelS(f), channelL(f), c.a);
1009        }
